The Prague Stock Exchange is at a negative at the end of trading
The Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses after the crash this morning.
Transactions with shares of the Czech Energy Company (<0xC4><0x8C>EZ) accounted for almost half of the daily trading.
The Prague Stock Exchange continued to plummet as early as Tuesday’s trading started, when it fell almost six percent.
This time, the decline in Wall Street shares is behind the decline.
This is how the market reacted to the vote in the US House of Representatives, which refused to support the plan to stabilise the financial sector there.
Fall of shares in Asia
Asian stock markets experienced a dramatic fall in stocks on Tuesday, although the indicators eventually canceled some of the losses over the course of the day.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng stock market index depreciated nearly four percent of the trade, but later canceled some of the losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which monitors Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, while markets in Shanghai closed.
The Sydney stock market lost more than five percent, but the losses fell to 4.3 percent.
According to the Taiwan Stock Exchange Index, the stock market fell by 3.6 percent.
“The timing of the U.S. rescue operation is uncertain and will affect the world’s financial markets,” said Joseph Yam, head of Hong Kong’s Financial Council.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines its monetary policy independently, i.e. independently of the Central Bank of China.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said that U.S. lawmakers should resume talks immediately and adopt a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries will feel the consequences.
The Bloodbath of American Stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, to which <0x24>700 billion (almost <0x24>12 trillion) should have been spent.
Legislators have thus ignored President Bush’s call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, U.S. stocks went through a bloodbath, and leading stock indices recorded the biggest drop in 20 years.
The Dow Jones fell nearly seven percent, the last time it fell was in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but as soon as it turned out that the proposal had not been adopted in the House of Representatives, the index began to fall free.
Congress Withdrew: US Government Could Pump <0x24>700 Billion in Banks
The U.S. Supreme Leaders of Congress and President George W. Bush’s government have agreed to broaden the deal and provide financial assistance to the U.S. financial system.
This will be voted on early next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in negotiations to approve the rescue plan in the form of <0x24>700 billion (about 12 trillion kroons) in financial assistance to the U.S. financial system.
But there's no victory yet.
Congress must complete some of the details of the agreement before it can publish the final form of the law and their vote.
The financial support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Reuters news agency Barney Frank, chairman of the Financial Institutions Committee, said on Sunday.
According to Senate sources, the bill will likely be voted on Wednesday as soon as possible.
According to economists, there should be an announcement that the rescue plan will be approved, which is the first important psychological factor in reviving the financial markets.
Due to the complexity of the mechanisms, however, a "sound-up" will follow.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have taken a big step.
We have resolved our differences of opinion on the form of the package to stabilize the market," Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat, told Bloomberg.
The final vote could take place on Sunday.
Legislators met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Saturday to formalize the government fund.
It should buy out the unsellable mortgages from financial corporations, which plunge financial corporations into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
“We are close to reaching a final agreement on a draft that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
The improvement plan needs to be continued, but I think we’re there,” Paulson said.
A signal for Asian trading
The global financial crisis is having a significant impact on stock markets, which are falling sharply.
Democrat senator Harry Reid of Nevada said lawmakers would seek a final settlement in Congress on Sunday.
This is intended to reassure investors before trading in Asian financial markets, where the time zone could be the first time that Congress’s decision could affect Monday’s trading.
However, it is not yet clear when the two chambers of the U.S. Congress will vote on the bill, nor is it clear whether the trial will not be blocked at the last minute due to a problem.
The legislators hope that the law will be approved in the next few days.
However, the law is still undergoing a number of changes.
The total amount intended to assist the scheme shall be divided into two parts.
The first <0x24>350 billion should be made available as soon as possible.
However, Congress could block the release of the remaining amount, which was set at an additional <0x24>100 billion and later at <0x24>350 billion, if it feels that the program is not fulfilling its function.
Bush assesses progress in negotiations
Although the President may veto this decision, Congress may override his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program remained, which was to acquire financial assets for the purchase of bad mortgage securities that were losing their value, as hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to repay their mortgages.
“We worked it all out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate should be able to vote on Monday,” Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
President Bush is also pleased with the progress made in the negotiations.
Tony Fratto, Bush’s spokesman, said the president was pleased with Saturday’s progress and appreciated “the bipartisan efforts to stabilize our money markets and protect our economy.”
Restriction of busus severance payments
Christopher Dodd, chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, said the legislators had agreed on the responsibility for the financial program, protecting taxpayers from losses, closing discounts, and timing of the financing plan.
The new law also limits the so-called busas severance payments of directors participating in the program and establishes a supervisory committee for the fund.
The fund should be managed by the Treasury Department.
"We've worked very hard on this, and we've made great progress towards an agreement that will work and benefit all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also includes assistance for homeowners who have problems with repayment.
The government should negotiate new installments for the mortgages it buys, with the aim of reducing the monthly installments of debtors and enabling them to keep their houses.
Marek: Spiritual aid
According to David Marek, Chief Economist at Patria Finance, the proposed project is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
“This is because it is not known by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be acquired.
This will determine how the financial sector and the government will allocate the losses to each other," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
According to Marek, it doesn’t matter if the plan is approved now or early next week.
“More importantly, Congress should decide this week to support the plan and give its blessing as soon as possible.
The spiritual importance of reaching an agreement on whether the plan will be approved is the most important thing at the moment," Marek said.
Pairing on the edge of the blade: MP3 players versus mobile.
We help you how to choose
While almost all mobile devices can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can be used to make a phone call.
This makes it clear that it is better to just buy a phone.
However, there are many reasons to buy a separate MP3 player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the needs of the prospective owner.
It’s probably hard to get a high-end, expensive turntable for your home to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc disc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not appear on vinyl records, but there is no objective reason for this from a qualitative point of view.
However, if your shelves are full of art rock, jazz, or blues vinyl records, you’re probably dreaming of having a record player like that.
This is similar to traveling, i.e. compressed - simplistic with MP3 music.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some, it may be unacceptable to give out eight thousand crowns for a player, as a Pink Floyd fan is likely to find it difficult to accept a 20 crown market headphones.
There are two extremes between which everyone has enough space.
There's a lot of choice.
Battery life also counts
Some high-end music players can do much more than just play music, but also something that most mobile phones just don’t.
No device is as universal as a phone.
In addition to the primary functions of phoning and texting, it can play music and video, record both, have a better or worse camera, and even navigate.
And if you consider smartphones and communicators, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
This is a miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can take photos.
However, multifunctional mobiles also have disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile, the more times the display sends it to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few mobile devices can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest) are significantly more powerful.
For cheap mobile phones, therefore, count on not playing for you for more than a few hours.
If you’re on the phone here or there, get a charger for your workplace just in case – this also applies to more expensive devices.
MP3 players will not have this problem, even the worst ones will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
The next issue arises when uploading music to mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector and, in addition, not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to the memory card, but only a few card readers can handle the miniature memory cards used in mobile devices without an adapter.
With a few exceptions (iPod), players do not need any special software.
It is enough to charge the device from the computer with music via USB.
Most mobile phones and players already create a music library that is sorted by the artist, album, genre name, or user rating, for example.
Some devices only depict a tree structure similar to Windows Explorer, and some know both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with an operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobiles know more
When choosing a specific device, ask about the battery life, memory capacity, sound output quality and type, and of course, the convenience of handling.
If the music is primarily used as a background for you and you only listen to it for a short time every day, for example on the tram, any MP3 player on your mobile phone is suitable for you.
This is something that any mobile phone can do.
You don’t even have to pay special attention to what music formats your mobile or player knows.
With MP3, they all cope, and the vast majority of the music you get will be in exactly this format.
MP3 is one of the most widely used, and in addition to it, the vast majority of the devices also cope with WMA format music.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPod) is less common.
Better mobiles also allow you to buy music online, for example.
It is enough to visit the relevant pages of the service provider (or other service provider) via the mobile internet and buy the song or album.
This service in itself can be a strong argument for the purchase of a music mobile.
Unfortunately, the providers’ offerings are poor and usually limited to annual radio hits.
The prices are not the lowest either.
In general, however, it can be assumed that the music industry will be dominated by this particular form of music sales (either via GSM, the Internet or wireless internet).
Most people carry their mobile devices with them all the time.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you’ll feel your mobile phone in your pocket while the forgotten MP3 player is lying at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry your headphones or at least your hands-free handsets.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker, which almost all mobile, but only a few MP3 players have.
For many, the biggest advantage of music mobile phones will probably be the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000 kroner.
Between three and four thousand crowns, you can get a pretty decent walkman.
Most of the time, however, you are limited by the lack of a traditional headphone output.
The best and most technically equipped phones with traditional 3.5mm hole headphones can cost up to 15,000 crowns.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, the ease of operation.
With the simplest - not necessarily the cheapest - players (see our selection), really everyone can cope.
Minimal function, handling comparable to a traditional cassette recorder or gramophone is obvious.
There is no risk of collapsing in the form of accidentally turned on mobile internet, and no risk of data transfer for the subsequent huge bill.
What device to choose
The cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have slots for removable memory cards (M2, microSD type, etc.).
Buying the right card can cost up to 2,000 kroner.
But be careful.
The basic types only support cards with a maximum capacity of up to 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones know what to do with up to 8GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and even want to buy a cheap MP3 player, choose Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Based on the capacity (up to 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than 1,100 kroner.
If you belong to the more demanding students, choose special mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsungs).
These devices also have a separate MP3 control button, so the convenience of the operation is closer to the MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, which has a walkman series of mobile phones, has the same user interface as the MP3 players sold separately.
MP3 players of the aforementioned brands can provide the same service in the same price range up to 4,000 kroner, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours).
The first virtual service provider will arrive in the Czech Republic later this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced and our service providers offer virtually the same services as their Western European partners.
Nevertheless, there is something lacking here - a virtual service provider that forces classic service providers to significantly reduce prices.
Maybe it won't be much longer.
On the Mobil.cz website we have written many times that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which pointed out that SMS prices in the Czech Republic are more expensive than in other EU countries.
After the latest move by the European Commission to regulate roaming charges, this may lead to a controversial situation - some customers of Czech mobile operators will find text messages from abroad cheaper than domestic ones.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple: there is no real competition.
This may sound contradictory, as we have three mobile networks and our penetration is well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are keen to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office, often agrees with this, and has previously stated on several occasions that there is no place for a new service provider in the Czech Republic.
Perhaps it is true that the classic provider with its own network probably doesn’t have too many chances anymore (however, it’s probably hard to find a frequency).
But there is another option - a virtual service provider.
It was the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market that led to a significant price reduction, after which the classic service providers had to react.
Even before big fish such as Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile came to the market in the UK, there were sounds similar to ours.
However, it has been proven that such providers have a place and can be truly successful.
However, for example, we do not have to go too far.
In February this year we informed you about the launch of Mobilking virtual service provider in Poland.
In less than six months, this service provider managed to attract more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest service provider there.
Meanwhile, behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which is also the owner of U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the possibility to focus on a much narrower target group.
In order to operate efficiently, you need far fewer customers than a traditional service provider.
It does not entail relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual service providers in the world thus tend to appear low-cost - they offer inexpensive calls and text messages, which, however, is often offset by fewer services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers text messages at least 50% cheaper than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on a target group can be quite a good move.
This service is specifically focused on men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - who they like, who they can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobil Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual service.
It is difficult to say whether the same idea as in Poland could work for us.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> doubts this: “The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which the majority of virtual service providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfactory in terms of service offerings.”
This is not possible in the Czech Republic, according to mobile operators.
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not seem too hopeful.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our region," said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, spokeswoman for Penta Finance Group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it has demonstrated that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not overly sympathetic to this idea.
On the contrary, they do their best to prevent any potential competition.
The GTS Novera Group has not concealed its interest in launching the virtual service provider for some time now, which is taking another step towards making Telefonica O2 a true competitor in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in providing not only fixed but also mobile telecommunication services to our customers.
And the sooner, the better.
We have discussed this possibility again with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl, the group's spokesman.
Maybe now's a better time.
Unofficial information suggests that we may be lucky enough to have our first virtual service provider by the end of the year.
His birth is surrounded by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At the moment, we do not believe that there is room for a fully-fledged virtual service provider in the Czech market.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very special.
Until now, we have not been approached by a single subject offering a complex and serious project in this area," he told Mobil.cz from Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica 02 press department.
Other operators also refer to the special situation of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1>, spokeswoman for T-Mobile, in an exceptional agreement with O2, adds: “We have not yet recorded any viable and mutually beneficial business projects on which to build further.”
And he added: "In the T-Mobile network by the end of the year, it is unlikely that any virtual service provider will appear.
We should have a concrete agreement on the table at the moment so that we can think about it in the short term.”
Vodafone will focus on fulfilling its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual service providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is what we consider to be the most rewarding for our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to partner to build shared networks for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - on the same footing with service providers
The behaviour of the mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of a new operator would increase competition, lead to lower prices and thus reduce their profits.
So why should we make it easier for such a competition to enter?
When service providers are interested in something, they are able to work together, as evidenced by the turmoil surrounding the birth of U:fon.
The biggest pressure on <0xC4><0x8C>TU was probably around the birth of T-Mobile’s U:fon.
The publicly available information on the <0xC4><0x8C>TU website bears witness to this.
But right now, the U:phone is a good argument for not allowing the virtual service provider to log in.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> added: "The competitive environment in the mobile market has recently been strengthened by the entry of the fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of a new player into the market and its services would be subject to high demands."
However, in view of this attitude of the mobile operators, the complete disinterest of the Czech regulators is absolutely staggering.
In the meantime, it is not just the attitude of <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which unfortunately, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, has no right to interfere in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
Only the Competition Authority is entitled to do so.
But the agency has a characteristic attitude towards the whole problem.
“The entry of the virtual service provider into the mobile market would only be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile service provider and the virtual service provider for the leasing of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contracts have been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for traditional service providers," said Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chlapua from the Department of External Relations of the Hungarian Competition Authority in answer to our question.
A statement made by the representatives of the service providers in this way would probably not surprise anyone.
However, it is more than odd that an agency that should represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, should ensure that no one can abuse its position on the market.
Especially if Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: “In foreign countries, where virtual service providers usually operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile services.”
However, it is probably not in the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to put pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and on the reduction of prices.
In this case, it is indeed shocking to see the very touching consistency of the reaction of the three mobile operators.
The question of whether this is really a coincidence is almost self-evident.
Just like at petrol stations, the exact same gas prices are surely the work of chance and tough competition.
"The Office has not discovered any signs of anti-competitive conduct in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the service providers have a leading position, i.e. a proportionately higher responsibility for their market activities.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market for virtual service providers are also likely to be lacking for the telecom regulator," Chalupa said.
The presentation of the market leader position is one of the many points of controversy.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>TU, according to which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, no Czech operator is in a leading position.
However, some legal experts also offer a different approach - the creation of a virtual service provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - relatively logically - has a monopoly on its own network.
So in a certain segment it is necessarily dominant.
But even if we did not accept this argument, it should be at least a warning for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators act in a strikingly similar way.
Meanwhile, a series of complaints from interested parties (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in the course of negotiations with all operators.
And shifting responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>TU is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS takes its hands off the whole case.
We have seen this in some similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted telecommunications law, the extension of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>’s powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications could not be implemented, although many experts hoped that this would improve the situation.
This should be well known to the representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS, but their interests are probably different.
It works when no one is watching.
In the meantime, the operation of some sort of fake virtual service provider will remain unnoticed, many of which are already operating in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own mobile phone service price lists, which, however, are only partially public.
These are multilevel marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies are usually only available to the selected ones.
The charm lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic corporate customer against the service provider, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a priority customer, you will then receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar advance purchases.
"If there were any cases of which you speak, it would be a breach of contract that we would deal with and that could lead to the termination of our cooperation with that company," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> answered our question about this problem.
But it's highly unlikely that news of this kind of activity hasn't reached the responsible people of the mobile operators.
In the case of the three companies mentioned above, there may be thousands of customers.
In the meantime, no service provider will defend itself against such a procedure.
These companies have not insignificant profits from their activities, and at the same time, unlike real virtual service providers, they do not threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns of possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, however, the services of these companies are used by only a negligible percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card on their phone is not in their name, so they cannot have it in its entirety, as is the case with the general customers of mobile operators.”
But that's what <0xC4><0x8C>TU should be weird about, at least.
In addition, another question arises for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile service providers are blinding themselves to the same procedure, why are they preventing the birth of a virtual service provider?
It should be added that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has a relatively strong authority to expose this type of activity, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with an explanation from the service providers that nothing of this kind was suspected and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be the most expensive
As has already been said a few times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has led to a noticeable decrease in the price of services.
In the meantime, in virtually every country where virtual service providers have been established, classic service providers have tried to more or less prevent their establishment.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small, perhaps too satisfied market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was precisely at these moments that regulators intervened, which were not protecting the interests of mobile operators, but the interests of their customers.
Then, either through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual service provider, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are handing the whole case over to each other.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that unclear competencies are good for them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider really does appear soon, the Czech mobile market may be back on the move.
If one of the service providers would allow the creation of a virtual mobile operator, <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will find it difficult to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of further interested parties.
And compared to the rest of Europe, we may not be able to make more expensive phone calls.
