Sleepless Nights for Hypo Real Estate Creditors
The German banking system is relatively stable, Federal Finance Minister Peer Steinbrück said last week.
It is fortunate that the politician used the word “relatively” and even made it clear that the German banking sector is not spared by crisis-like developments.
Because that happened this weekend.
Dax-listed Munich-based real estate company Hypo Real Estate (HRE) has received billions of dollars in loans from a consortium of German banks to protect itself against market turbulence.
A person familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that the loan subsidies would amount to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>35 billion.
Hypo Real Estate will only have to pay interest on the part used.
The money comes partly from private and partly from public banks.
The background is the losses of the Depfa subsidiary.
According to a newspaper report, Depfa, which provides public funding, has lent money for long-term projects and has refinanced itself for an extremely short term - which is now impossible due to the mistrust in the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank’s cash reserves decreased by 95 percent to EUR 2.37 million, and its equity ratio also declined moderately, from 1.6 to 1.45%.
Current income and net income from cash transactions fell to zero compared to the same period last year, while income from claims credits and certain securities, as well as from the liquidation of the provisions of the credit business, declined by more than 70 percent to EUR 5 million.
It was only thanks to higher revenues from the reimbursement of the ex-post settlement costs of the restructuring of the former Depfa Group, as well as the reimbursement of interest pursuant to the Tax Decree and the transactions for the companies belonging to the Group that the revenue gap of around 16% was relatively moderate.
After the privatisation in 1990, the former state-financed company first speculated on corporate real estate loans, which were later segregated in Aeral Bank.
Due to the low potential of classical public funding, Depfa has invested more heavily in infrastructure projects and private-public partnerships (PPPs) with the state, and has expanded its activities internationally.
The value of the subsidiaries must now be written off by Hypo Real Estate, which has a "significant impact" on the group's profit and loss account, the statement said.
In fact, no dividends were paid.
Dividends were cut to a third by 2007.
Hypo Real Estate has become a major state and infrastructure funder since the takeover of Depfa.
It is more dependent on interbank market refinancing than other financial institutions as it does not have client deposits.
With the collapse of the American investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, lending between banks has slowed down as banks keep their liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate needs short-term assets annually to refinance part of Depfa’s loan portfolio – some <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>50 billion.
According to a statement from Hypo Real Estate, the group’s funding needs are covered by the loan for a foreseeable period of time and the company is protected from “the influence of the international financial markets that are currently largely unworkable.”
According to other sources, the refinancing will be secured by the end of 2009 thanks to the money.
On the other hand, HRE Chairman Georg Funke stated that the Hypo Real Estate Group would not have to use the financial markets for a foreseeable period of time.
The Federal Bank of Germany and the Federal Financial Services Authority (BaFin) consider that the marketability of the Hypo Real Estate group is now assured.
This gives hope to the bank’s shareholders and creditors.
But because of the dynamic and immeasurable nature of the crisis, they cannot be certain.
It is not even inconceivable that you do not need to make full use of the funding.
But the opposite cannot be ruled out either.
After Saturday’s late-night news that the bank was still on the brink of bankruptcy, its temporary rescue could not reassure the spirits.
The share price fell by 75 percent to EUR 3.30.
By contrast, bond prices hold up fairly well.
While debt ranked first hardly changes, the prices of subordinated bonds have fallen significantly.
In particular, the crisis affects the bonds of the former subsidiary, Württemberg Hypo, and, as is available, the maturity beyond 2009.
While Hypo Real Estate bonds used to appear to be a speculative investment alternative, their value stability is now to be considered dependent on the stability of the international financial system due to the escalation of the banking crisis and the fact that the financial institution almost brought the crisis home with the takeover of Depfa.
As long as central banks, governments and less vulnerable business banks are still ready to support the system, it is possible to start from the timely repayment of annuities.
Or there will be something that almost no one now dares to hope to overcome the financial crisis in the next 15 months.
However, in the light of the reports of partial nationalization, the probability bounded by certainty has now been reduced to mere legitimate hope.
For long-term lenders, the decision to give up their investment can cause sleepless nights.
Short-term investors can, however, use the sale to create a reserve for taxes on exchange rate gains in the coming years.
Sylvana and the Secrets of the Inside Box
When 16-year-old Sylvana Hiltrop has to introduce herself at Tachibana Highschool on her first day of school, the girls start giggling: The German girl is totally "kawaii"!
What does that mean?
Sylvana already knows the word manga - in the new exchange student blog she talks about Japan.
"The first day of school in Japan.
I was so excited.
On my way to school, I was inflamed.
I live on the outskirts of Tokyo, towards Kavasaki, and I travel 40 minutes by train to Tachibana High School.
I had to find my way alone, but fortunately I didn’t get lost.
It seems that the beginning of teaching in Tachibana is not taken as seriously as at home in Lower Saxony.
Students start to squeeze in from 8:00 until 8:40 a.m., a short conversation starts with the teacher, the "home room".
But before I started teaching, it was my turn to introduce myself.
I’m not the kind of person who likes to talk to people, especially in front of a class of 40 students.
Since I didn’t have my school uniform yet, I put on an old skirt from my hostess, with a blouse, blue knee stockings and black leather shoes.
In this dress I stood before your catheter and tried to pronounce everything correctly: "Sajonara, vo se Sylvana ..." - My name is Sylvana, I am from Germany, and my birthday is in a week.
At that moment, I was very happy that I had started learning the language for over two years.
All 31 girls were whispering, smiling and waving, and I kept hearing the word "kawai."
I know this from my manga.
It's part of the basic vocabulary of Japanese girls, and it means "cute, sweet."
Then I hurried to my place.
The girl sitting next to me smiled broadly, feeling honored to have the exchange student seated next to her.
The rest of the clock was quite calm, but when the bell rang, they rushed in orderly.
Everyone talked and laughed, and with their questions they bore a hole in my abdomen -- though it was quite difficult to understand the Japanese's English.
During the break, everyone unpacked their booths.
My host prepared a lunch for me too - it's completely different from the boring German brunch sandwiches.
I got spicy rice, little sausages, lettuce made from cucumbers and algae, fruit and a kind of tofu rolled meat.
Most of the time, I have no idea what I'm eating here in Japan.
The dishes look strange and have a completely new taste.
In fact, everything is very delicious.
Yeah, except for the salty plum sauce, brrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrr
In Japanese schools, bungalows are not just lunches.
Sometimes a girl gives a boy a self-made bento, which she puts together especially artistically - in the hope of getting to know the boy more closely during the lunch break.
I read about it in my manga comics.
I wonder if I can observe this here as well.
“Why Japan?” my friends asked me when I told them that I wanted to go to school in Tokyo for a year.
I always said,
"Because it just fascinates me."
After all, I have been reading manga for years.
And to better understand the comics and the culture described in them, I started learning Japanese sometime.
It was clear to me that I would have to travel here sometime.
Because I'm attracted to tradition and customs.
And these are very cherished here.
Japan, on the one hand, is a country of the latest techniques and trends - on the other hand, it is strict, disciplined and traditional.
And because everything is so well organized, I’ve never felt lost, even though Tokyo is the biggest city I’ve ever seen.”
Rats have emotions, too.
A rat or a moth is fleeing in the face of danger. Does that mean he feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that animals also have emotions.
But how can we examine whether they feel the same when they act like us?
In the online journal "Edge" famous scientists have been publishing their articles for years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE looks at the answers to the question "What do you think is real without being able to prove it?" in one of its series.
I believe that animals have emotions and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it, and it is true that we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
In this case, however, we can at least hope that the basic configuration of all human brains is the same.
However, as we examine other species and dissect the issues of perception or consciousness in general, we come to a difficult terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, he does what many other animals do: pretending to be dead, fleeing or attacking.
People behave in a similar way, from which some researchers deduce comparable subjective experiences.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult for us to transfer our own subjective experiences to those of animals.
On the one hand, circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and executive/control functions).
This vast area is more developed in man than in other primates, and appears to be completely absent in other organisms.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, such as knowing who we are, or in the case of the ability to plan and make decisions, it is reasonable to assume that man is different even from other primates.
Another dramatic feature lies in the linguistic nature of man: Since much of human experience is related to language, it is often claimed that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals can be excluded.
However, even if it were not dependent on language, it would certainly be influenced by language, so that animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is likely to be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness is like in other animals.
If consciousness cannot be measured as an internal and subjective thing, and it cannot be analyzed due to special hardware based on our own experience, then its research poses serious problems for us.
Most of my explanations are about the content of conscious living, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that is probably more accessible to science.
The consciousness processes of animals could be examined regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in experiments on the short-term memory of primates, especially in the example of visualization.
However, in this hypothesis, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick have examined, they rely more on the neural connections of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both may or may not be the same.
Interestingly, this hypothesis also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the formation of visualization.
What does this mean for emotions?
This is due to the fact that an emotional system, like that of fear, is activated in a brain that is aware of its own actions.
