In this part of the Education Monitor, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the candidates’ views on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, an experienced researcher at the Pacific Institute for Public Policy Research and senior director of education research, co-author of the book “Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs School Choice.”
It is not easy to please voters from Spanish-speaking areas.
Barack Obama’s proposals on education are also included.
According to Obama’s campaign, “African-American and Spanish-speaking students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” and this is true.
In order to overcome such performance gaps, Obama’s Education Plan explicitly supports, among other things, “transitional bilingual education” for English learners.
At the same time, the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on school education in non-English, will outweigh his interest in overcoming the big performance gaps.
