A Separate City, the Pride and Trials of Blacks
In the Greater Orlando amusement park, a few miles away from everything that glitters, is loud and powerful, hides a quiet small town where the pride and complications of the African-American life experience were born.
Eatonville, the first purely black city to be integrated into the country and the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as he described it in 1935: "The five lakes, three croquettes, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava and two school towns, without prison."
It's now a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have attended the annual Zora Festival, a series of celebrations held in Eetonville in honor of Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
Yet in many ways, the city that he described and made a tourist attraction, which is also included in the Florida Guidebook published by the Crisis Federal Writers Project, is separate from its surroundings.
It is as independent, dignified, and self-contained as it was in the 1930s, when, according to Hurston, city blacks in Florida were often reluctant to share their true thoughts with white people who “know so little about us that they don’t know what they’re missing.”
Even in the year that the black presidential candidate Barack Obama encouraged an open exchange of views on the racial issue, many here are distrustful of the outsider’s gaze.
“We are very careful how our story is told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, who has lived here all his life and is a member of the city’s oldest church.
"You have to tell it right."
Eatonville has long been characterized by the paradox of victory and struggle.
At the same time, it is a historical model of black standing, and at the same time a community of almost 2,400 people, where the poverty rates are double the national average.
Partly a literary node, and partly an example of the sometimes despised, sometimes praised, southern, urban, black culture that flourishes in the shade of oak trees, as a result of American slavery.
It is not surprising, then, that the people here are proud and defensive at the same time.
The image of Eatonville has been important since Zora (here everyone calls Hurston that).
In books written in an honest, strong dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937), he introduced his hometown to the world.
The five paragraphs of the Florida guidebook transformed the city, which lies next to Route 17, a road that leads from the long-forgotten center of Florida to one of the sites of black history and human drama.
Hurston, who was as brave as the drums in life and literature, introduced his readers to Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then looked into more intimate spheres.
He wrote: "To the right of the road we find the modern public school, on a brown background with a white border, carefully maintained courtyards and playgrounds, which Howard Miller tends, though he can hardly read and write."
She mentioned the widow Dash's new husband, and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of drinks and anything you might need in the temporary accommodation."
In a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with autonomy, but also with illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Clearly, the Fodor's guidebook presented it differently.
This description didn’t really please everyone.
"Zora told things the way they were," said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls, who was immortalized by Hurston by quoting the slick songs men sang about their beauty.
He added: “Some people didn’t like it.”
Hurston is still remembered here as the living eccentric who often visited home after his family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
The 77-year-old Augustus Franklin recalled that when Hurston stormed into the city, he usually arrived unannounced in a roaring Chevrolet, smoking cigarettes and wearing long pants to a city where people are still proud of their dignified dress.
Most people were fascinated, Franklin said, but many were foreshadowed.
"People were always happy to see Zora," Franklin said.
However, on the terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, he added, swinging in his chair, "He never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor, and his books were not republished.
Along with most of the world, it seemed that Eatonville had forgotten about it.
Although he was once a popular writer, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, he was buried in an unmarked tomb in Fort Pierce, Florida, where he used to live.
There were no major commemorations or large public readings in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood how much it enriched the world or what it left us at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's biography, "Wrapped in a Rainbow," published in 2003.
The turning point came in 1980.
Orange County officials wanted to build a five-lane road through the city instead of the two-lane main street, Kennedy Avenue, which played an important role in community life.
The expanding Orlando has already penetrated the state-bound Interstate 4 highway on the western border of the city.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering after a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, among other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, racially mixed struggles brought hatred to the community.
"At that time, a group of white boys came over and threw oranges and other things at those on the side of the road," Franklin said.
"There was a woman who died in this.
They threw a watermelon out of a car."
In a letter to The Orlando Sentinel in 1955, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's decision to impose forced integration, stating that "the Brown v. Board of Education decision is more offensive than respectful of my race."
Today, residents say that although the de-segregation of schools was positive in some respects, it weakened the cohesion of the people of Eetonville and undermined the self-confidence of young people.
“Black children are accustomed to being hugged—I remember that—the man hugged his teacher both in the morning and in the evening,” said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins, executive director of a nonprofit organization called “Let’s Keep the Eatonville Community.”
"This lasted as long as students and teachers came from a common place," he added.
“We didn’t hug our white teacher because he was a white teacher – I mean, there were cultural differences between us,” Nathiri said.
However, human rights have helped many other Zora Neale Hurstons rise—black writers, actors, and artists who have transcended prejudice, as she has done, with such optimistic self-confidence and lines as, “How can anyone deprive themselves of the pleasure of my company?
This is incomprehensible to me.”
In 1975, Alice Walker pilgrimed to Hurston's unmarked tomb and began to struggle to restore her reputation.
Five years later, a highly acclaimed biography of Hurston, written by Robert E. Hemenway, was placed on the shelves of bookstores, and was once again a role model for America.
The road construction project was about to begin when Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the spotlight.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw him as a savior.
The community started organizing a Hurston festival in 1988 to show what the county would ruin with its main road.
Thousands of fans have come to the opening event two years later, and many have since returned to the ceremony every January.
Several years later, the county withdrew from its road construction proposal.
"With the five-lane highway, the community has been revived at full speed, which is a real civil pride," Nathiri said.
Boyd said, “Zora saved Eatonville.”
The victory over the road construction project helped change the city’s image of itself.
Increasing numbers of people living outside the city, such as lawyer Rachelle Munson, who started attending church here in 1993, began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the National Historic List in 1998.
In 2006, a new one-storey library (named after Hurston, of course) was opened on Kennedy Avenue.
Eatonville remains Florida's cuckoo-egg: less than ten kilometers from downtown Orlando, but sometimes it feels like a suburban side street during summer rain; as small as when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Ninety percent of the population is black.)
They still receive with caution outsiders who come here in search of the story of Eatonville.
Most interviews require prior permission, and some things — such as Eatonville’s oldest fresco, painted by a white man and depicting blacks working in the fields — are not allowed to be photographed.
Many people in Eatonville, including the confident teacher Jones, who is particularly attracted to bright red, fear that their separate community will be misunderstood.
And yet, as the Hurston Festival expanded, the pride of the hometown grew.
Young people, in particular, increasingly view Eatonville as the way Hurston saw his race: wonderful, with all its problems and everything, neither better, nor worse, as proud, as creative, as diligent, as foolish, and as confused as other racial and ethnic groups in America.
A sincere civic affection comes from the words of Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return after graduating from college to work for a local government or police station that he thinks needs help.
And it seems the younger ones have also learned to correctly describe Eatonville, such as the 11-year-old Winter Park twins: Alondra and Alexia Kenon.
"Most people who just travel through here think this city is nothing compared to the rest," said Alondra Kenon recently after the service on Sunday.
"But if someone stops and takes some time to get to know his history, then this is a very beautiful city."
