“I don’t take pictures on stage because I want to introduce the artist from a personal point of view.” – Günther Bauer
No set, no frills, no dance shoes.
The grandmasters of flamenco are close by, without the excitement of the performance: so that we can get to know the everyday faces of the dancers.
On the one hand, the artist.
Ordinary people, on the other hand.
And these two sides cannot be separated, except in intimate moments away from the audience, when one can glimpse at a personal gesture, grasp the depth of a caught gaze, or marvel at the beauty of the inactive but expressive hand of the artist who is about to perform outside the stage.
The German photographer Günther Bauer combines the theatricality of singers, dancers and guitarists with this lesser-known everyday side of the masters in his photo series Flamenco-people.
Through the photos, he presents the distinctive iconography of flamenco from different perspectives.
The exhibition, which is part of Flamenco’s Photography Month, “reflects the increasing international importance of flamenco every day,” the author says, adding that the Flamenco-people “could be anyone, as the viewer realizes that these images do not represent the artists in a typical way.
These people on the street are artists who can bring passion, sadness, joy to the stage... and captivate the audience.
Stage photography, however, is not suitable for capturing their personality.
Their personality and character reside in the depths of their being.
I wanted to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the flamenco grandparents with the help of a camera.”
With the impetus of the Cante de las Minas festival, Bauer embarked on his long journey in 1997, taking portraits of flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers using a disc camera.
These portraits evoke classic photography thanks to the camera and theme selection.
However, the application of different stylistic tools breaks with traditional visual representations and suggests modernity. The following idea faithfully reflects Bauer's idea of flamenco: "This is music with traditional roots, but it changes from day to day and is always fascinating."
Not the dance, not the singing or the music itself, but rather the personality and character of the artist enchant the audience.
The guiding motif of the works that can be viewed in the gallery of El P<0xC3><0xB3>toma is the search for the encounter with the essential, the artistic vaas, which becomes visible through the way of perception, existence and presentation.
Famous flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo are the hallmarks of this photo collection featuring almost 60 artists.
The project has also become a flamenco anthology, which will soon include an album featuring the portraits presented at the exhibition.
Two years ago Bauer’s passion for portraits prompted him to repeat the idea with the series “Portraits of veteran athletes” (“SportARTproject”).
Although the concept of Flamenco-people is slightly different, the photographer adds: "I really like to photograph people, get to know them and enter their lives for a longer or shorter moment.
In my opinion, the most difficult genre of photography is portrait.
You meet people, you meet people you don’t even know, or people who only take a few minutes to take photos.
But in spite of these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas.
The exhibition Flamenco-people, selected from the portraits of contemporary flamenco, can be seen in the El Photomata Gallery at the Alameda de Hércules parallel calle de la Mata 20 until 16 October.
