Recurrent drunk drivers will be forced to install "Alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior would require drivers to install a device that would prevent them from starting the vehicle if the driver was drunk or not blowing into the device.
The proposal was presented in June and is currently being dealt with by the Public Prosecutor’s Office, according to which the pilot project will last for one year.
As the goal of the project is to restore traffic, the driver will also have to take a repeat course on traffic education.
In addition to the Public Prosecutor’s Office for Traffic Safety, the General Directorate for Transport (DGT) and the Institute of Car Safety Technology Foundation (FITSA) are also participating in the experiment.
According to statistics, 30-75% of drivers arrested several times for drunk driving are back in the car.
This would be prevented by Alcolock, because the system connected to the vehicle detects the alcohol level of the air in which it is inhaled. If it is higher than permitted, or if the driver did not inhale at all, the system will not allow the car to start.
The cost of more than <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1,000 would be borne by the offender.
A 2007 U.S. study showed that vehicles equipped with such instruments could reduce the number of violations by up to 65% in the first year after installation.
In Spain, it is estimated that this rule could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure focuses on violations for two reasons: on the one hand, it makes it easier to prevent them from becoming a criminal offence,
on the other hand, it is easier to implement, as the legal reform is being implemented in the usual way, while the necessary criminal justice reform would require a constitutional amendment.
The instrument is not yet available in any commercial form on the Spanish market, although it has already been installed in experimental mode in some industrial and public service vehicles.
Tomorrow, the House of Representatives will vote on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which, following the French model, calls for the system to be incorporated into school buses.
