People who talk in their dreams
Some kids talk at night.
I am not talking about those who wake up and are fully alert about what happened to them that day, but about those who talk while they sleep.
The phenomenon may seem frightening at first, but in fact it is completely harmless.
This benign sleep disorder is called somniloquism.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
I'm sure more of them have been told he was talking last night.
In terms of its frequency, it can be completely rapsodic (for example, it occurs only once in a high-fever illness) or more regular (once a day, a week, or a month), and usually the child does not remember anything the next day.
Its appearance cannot be traced back to a single cause.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, night waking, bedtime urination (enuresis nocturna) or sleepwalking, but this is not legal.
As already mentioned, a high fever condition, or even a stressful situation, or an increased state of excitement, can be an accompanying phenomenon.
In any case, it has not been studied so far.
The intensity of speech is also very variable.
It may be quiet, calm, composed of incoherent words, or murmur, but in contrast, it may also take the form of shouting, crying, or prolonged speech.
If the phenomenon is very intense, it is advisable to observe the child and consult a specialist. The examination may reveal whether there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety, and thus may offer a solution.
As mentioned above, it is a benign phenomenon and therefore there is no cure unless it is associated with another form of sleep disorder that can be treated (such as insomnia or stress).
However, there are a few things you can do, here is a bouquet of preventive measures:
Make sure your child is calm before going to bed.
Choose reassuring games and avoid watching fear-inducing or more aggressive TV shows or series.
Children who are nervous or have difficulty relaxing will be taught a few relaxation methods to help them find inner peace.
This helps the child to sleep more peacefully.
If you start talking while you sleep, try to stay calm.
Remember, it's harmless to the child, and the next day they won't remember anything.
Useful advice
Do not wake the child.
It would be unnecessary, because the child is unconscious, but would fall out of sleep.
Even though he talks, he actually keeps sleeping and resting.
Remember, if the phenomenon is accompanied by severe anxiety several times, it is recommended to consult a specialist or to find out what provokes a high degree of anxiety in the child.
If you speak clearly (this is the rarest case), do not start asking questions to find out anything from him.
It would be superfluous anyway, because when you sleep, you are not conscious enough to gather your thoughts.
On the other hand, you can only hear the speech, but do not see the associated dream images, so be careful with the interpretation of what you have heard and any conclusions you may have.
Never tell a child that they can ask him about his secrets at night.
Not even a joke.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
So the most important thing is not to worry, as it is only a few minutes of harmless episode.
