Blood is safe again.
President Francine Décary had good reason to celebrate, because Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood donating societies in the world.
Most importantly, he managed to regain people’s trust, which was severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood supply managed by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Supply Service was infected with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and the general uproar, the Canadian government launched an official investigation in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, with the aim of clarifying the circumstances that led to the tragedy and formulating proposals to avoid similar incidents in the future.
While Judge Krever delayed his report, some provinces set up their own committee to design a new blood treatment system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this task.
The Gélineau and Krever reports led to the creation of two blood supply services in Canada: the Hema-Québec service in Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Supply Society, which is responsible for supplying all the other provinces and two territories.
“When Hema-Québec started in 1998, just 38% of people had confidence in Quebec’s blood supply system,” Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was desperate.
“In the following years, however, we have managed to regain people’s trust as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in the field.” Décary proudly states that in early 2008, almost 94% of the population of Quebec considered Héma-Québec reliable.
However, Dr. Décary does not forget that “trust is an extremely fragile thing.”
Since the establishment of Héma-Québec on 28 September 1998, the precautionary principle has been applied.
During this period, a number of cases of bovine spongiform encephalopathy, the new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, have been exposed in Europe, says the doctor, who has been running the company since it was founded in 1998.
“We had no idea whether this disease was spread by blood.
That is why we have relied on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gelineau reports. According to this, if we are unsure about this and there is a risk of developing a serious disease, then we should apply exclusion measures. In this case, we were talking about Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which causes brain lesions and thus inevitably leads to death.
Therefore, in April 1999, we did not accept blood from people who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980.
A few years ago, it was established beyond any doubt that the disease was spread by blood.
This case convinced us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a technique appeared on the market that allows for a much more sensitive diagnosis of the HIV virus. This is the nucleic acid test (NAT), which is able to detect the virus itself directly in the blood of donors, rather than the antibodies against the virus on which previous tests were based.
The NAT test allowed us to shorten the window period from infection until we can detect the virus in the blood using our technical tools, the expert explains.
This period could be shortened to less than a week.
Thus, they significantly reduced the risk of unknowingly contaminating the bloodstream by blood donors, and that this could not be detected.
These developments have greatly reduced the risk of AIDS spreading through blood transfusions.
Today, the risk of getting HIV-infected blood is 12 million to one.
“In other words, we should allocate 12 million blood products until someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it would take more than 24 years for such a case to occur and someone to become infected with HIV through a blood product.
I think that today anyone can accept or prescribe blood transfusions to restore health, says the number one leader of Héma-Québec.
“The challenge for the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
You never know what kind of new pathogen will enter the system.
After all, it was only last year that the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, enters the blood by an insect bite.
Therefore, we must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary continued, stressing that, in addition to emergency reserves, Héma-Québec must provide for sufficient permanent reserves.
“As the population ages, the demand is also increasing.
Because anti-cancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has an impact on the blood donor population, as the number of people in the network who are capable of donating blood is only 3% of the population of Quebec.
However, any healthy person at least 18 years of age who meets the eligibility criteria should donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of applicants do not accept blood because they are infected with, for example, AIDS or malaria, and those who have been to a country where malaria is devastating are not eligible to donate blood for a year.
“With these three percent, we have enough reserves to meet the needs of hospitals.
It's very rare that we're running out of supplies.
We need to increase the number of blood donors as the existing ones age, because after a while they can no longer donate blood.
But it is very difficult to convince people to donate blood, and it is even harder to keep them and make them regular donors.
In today’s fast-paced world, a man has barely an hour to go and donate blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of <0x24>297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products but also human tissues, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin tissue, which is used almost exclusively for severely burned people.
These tissues are analysed, transformed and frozen and then placed at Héma-Québec, which also manages one public stem cell bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, once treated only as medical waste, can produce blood rich in stem cells, enabling the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the inclusion in our bank of the 1,000th umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to take more than 1,000 new samples each year.
At the beginning of next year, we will probably start offering them for organ transplants,” said Dr. Décary, who says that the umbilical cord blood removal program is very popular today.
“Many mothers are saddened that they don’t have the opportunity to do so,” he said, as Héma-Québec is unable to make this complex and costly program available in all hospitals in Quebec.
