The Orwellian Speech of Barrick Gold
In the September 17 issue of Le Devoir, a letter was published from Patrick J. Garver, deputy chairman and chief executive officer of the Barrick Gold Mine in Canada.
In response to Orwell’s remarks, Garver claims that the world’s largest gold-producing company has filed a <0x24>6 million defamation suit against three authors and a low-cost publishing company to initiate a so-called “public debate.”
Although judges are independent and impartial, their decision, especially in defamation cases, is not based on the truth, but on the law.
Not surprisingly, Garver kept a deep silence about this fundamental difference.
Is it really the best way for Barrick Gold to have a public debate, to destroy anyone who has a position against his?
Regardless of the outcome of the lawsuit, the authors and publishers of Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums of money on defense and combat in an unequal battle with an army of lawyers on the other side supported by almost inexhaustible resources from the mining industry.
In such an unequal struggle, by the way, the tactic of destroying the defendant and making a friendly settlement is often used, not only to silence the opponents, but even to intimidate those who would try to reconsider the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, he should have expressed his views before the public.
Although in many other countries where Barrick Gold operates, this is different, in Canada the parties to the dispute usually do not beat each other with sticks, but express their thoughts.
The mine would therefore have sufficed to open its books and files and prepare for a real debate in the press, media, and publications, paying independent research groups that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust the public, and in a single move, he swept away petitions and letters to protect the authors of Noir Canada.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he can initiate a 'public' debate if, at the same time, he disregards the opinion of this public?
In the vice president’s mind, this word probably only means paid lawyers, not the total population of Canada: the meaning of the term is thus greatly reduced.
In a democratic state, even those who denigrate others are entitled to freedom of speech.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the authors and publishers of Noir Canada are supported by the public mainly because they condemn the rude practices of the mine.
Public opinion is ready to listen to Barrick and make a verdict, but it would do so on the basis of civilized arguments, rather than a lawsuit aimed at silence for many. (In connection with the term "public debate", Barrick Gold recently wrote to the Noir Canada authors to refrain from using this term.)
In addition to Garver’s surreal discussions, Barrick Gold’s policy openly attacks the freedom of university research and the search for truth, which are the building blocks of any democratic society.
