The Psychology of Overbidding: Why Do We Spend More Money?
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overvalue the goods.
Neuroscientists and economists at the University of New York have uncovered the neurological and economical foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the journal Science, people don’t want to lose in a competition such as eBay auctions, so they tend to pay too high a price.
The research attempted to map the neurological pattern of this "play" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers participated in the lottery, the other group participated in a player auction, while using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) to study the active brain areas of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction game, in which an essential element was the overbidding of the other party, the striatum, a subcortical complex called the striatum, became intensely active when the game was lost.
This area of the brain, in addition to several other functions, plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the rise in price can be explained by avoiding the fierce reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
Three groups bid against one partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they placed their bets.
Another group was also promised that if they got out of the game, they would be rewarded with another <0x24>15 in cash.
The third group, on the other hand, was paid <0x24>15 before the auction, but the group members lost that money in the event of a losing auction.
The only difference between the two groups, therefore, was that they emphasized winning for one group and losing for the other.
Proving the neuroscientists' hypothesis, however, members of the team playing "against loss" were willing to bet higher than the control and "win" groups.
“These results cannot be deduced from any previous economic theory.
Until now, they have only explained the phenomena of the auction with the joy of victory and risk evasion.
“Only neurological imaging techniques have helped to resolve the contradiction between these two theories, and we have now come to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide are infected with chronic hepatitis B or C, and chronic liver disease is one of the leading causes of death in Hungary.
The number of people living with hepatitis in Hungary is estimated to be 100,000, but only 7,000 are treated, which is due to the fact that patients are often unaware that they are infected.
The term hepatitis is a common name for liver infections caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, characterized by inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases they cause differ.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, with infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (egg, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Travellers should be protected against the A and B viruses, there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected food, generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal complaints, nausea.
After this, yellowing of the skin and whites of the eyes develops, the stool is light, the urine turns dark, healing can take two to three weeks.
Worldwide, one million people die each year from the most severe form of hepatitis B, liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected receives medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated, it can also lead to cirrhosis of the liver, liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, because the pathogen insidiously destroys the cells of the liver, in many cases the first symptoms appear only after 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to carry out early prevention and regular screening tests.
In three groups, the incidence of these diseases is much higher than average: among people who had had blood transfusions before 1991, among drug users and among tattooed people.
The number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C virus is currently around 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult a GP if any symptoms of unknown origin are detected.
With timely detection, the disease can be cured, the virus can be eliminated from the body, thus eliminating the infectivity and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first held in 2004 by organisations representing patients around the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God hurt less?
According to a recent study, religious beliefs act as a kind of painkiller that may have facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment to investigate how belief in God affects people’s sense of pain, according to the British Telegraph.
In a rather bizarre study, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were electroshocked while they were all studying a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
The results showed that Catholics were able to rule out most of the pain.
Thanks to the technology that scans the human brain, it was also found that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
The study is the first in a series of research involving academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university.
The study was carried out precisely by attaching a sparking device to the test subject’s left hand, which provided the electroshock.
The researchers asked participants to look closely at two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and Leonardo da Vinci's painting of the Lady with Hermelin in the 15th century.
The authors of the study hoped that the spectacle of the Virgin Mary would bring about a religious state among believers, while the image of da Vinci was chosen because it was not too different from the other and was thought to have a soothing effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, during which time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive episodes while either looking at the religious theme or the general picture.
Catholics reported that when they saw the Virgin Mary, they felt “safe” as if they had “taken care of her” and “been calm and at peace.”
When looking at a religious image, they reported 12 percent less pain than when they saw Leonardo’s work in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who was himself involved in the study, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any powerful image, even with atheists, only the right photo needs to be found.
"We should find a picture of someone they feel very positive about, like a mother or a father," he said.
