A smart car imitates the flight of a bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop collision avoidance technologies, if not the imitation of obstacle detectors in the natural world?
Bees, for example.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, Bumblebees gave Nissan engineers the strategic starting point for building the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has developed the BR23C bio-imitation car robotic control system, a robotic mini-car with bee features, with the ultimate goal of helping design a system that eliminates all collisions.
While flying, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is in fact very similar to our safety cover,” explained Kazuhiro Doi, Director of Technology PR and R&D Branding at the exhibition.
An important role is played by the complex eye of the uterus, which can see in all directions from an angle of view of more than 300 degrees.
To replicate the function of the complex eye, the engineers turned to the idea of a laser distance meter.
It identifies obstacles within a distance of 2 meters in a 180-degree field of vision in front of the BR23C, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately transformed into a collision avoidance operation.
Within a fraction of a second, the obstruction is detected, and the car robot, imitating the movements of the uterus, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to avoid a collision.
Unlike any current system, this avoidance manoeuvre takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If this were not the case, the car-robot would not be able to react fast enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car-robot project.
It should react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety shield, a layer within which a collision is currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process should reflect what a bee does in order to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, the deviation must not be upwards, downwards or diagonally, it must be only two-dimensional and only in the direction of the rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the endless possibilities available to bees to bypass other bees, only rotating movement and acceleration, as well as deceleration, were used as an available option for the car robot.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer service life than the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, instinctive intelligent reaction is important, not the ability to process data, even less the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process and respond to a few input signals per second.
There is no need to preserve them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so you will constantly use only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
There is no need for gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of an immediate bypass technology, which Nissan estimates will be able to enter production vehicles within 10 years.
Additional applications may include the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to the specified destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
