Industrial prices continue to rise
The domestic sales prices of industry increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, reports the Central Statistical Office.
Prices of industrial export sales were 1.1% higher than in July 2008, down 3.9% year-on-year.
As a result of the changes in domestic and export prices, industrial producer prices were 0.7 per cent higher than in the previous month and 3.2 per cent higher than in the previous year.
Compared to the previous month, the domestic sales prices of the industry increased only marginally, by 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices of manufacturing industries also increased slightly by 0.1 percent compared to July.
The biggest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), mainly due to the 4.6 per cent monthly price increase in the manufacture of handbags and straps and 2.5 per cent monthly price increase in the manufacture of footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and product manufacturing sector (1.6%).
There were price decreases in the petroleum processing (1.4%), electrical machine and instrument manufacturing (0.9%) and, to a minimum, in the wood processing (0.1%).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities did not change.
In the other manufacturing sectors, we measured a price increase of between 0.2 percent and 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector, which represents a significant part of the domestic sales of the industry, prices increased by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the spillover effect of the official gas price increase implemented from 1 July.
Compared to the domestic sales of the manufacturing sectors, prices in the petroleum processing sector increased the most in twelve months (32.4%).
In the manufacturing of metalworking products, the price increase was 13.2%, while in the food, beverage and tobacco manufacturing sector, which is the dominant weight, an increase of 11% was observed.
The decrease in prices occurred in the textile, textile goods and electrical machinery and instruments sectors (2.5 per cent) and in the manufacturing of electrical machinery and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the other manufacturing sectors, the rate of price increase was between 0.6 percent and 9.1 percent.
In the manufacturing industry as a whole, prices have increased by 10.2% over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors were 18.7 percent higher than a year earlier.
Among the intended groups of sectors, domestic sales showed the largest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) in the sectors producing investment goods in August.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices grew by 0.3 per cent, and in the energy and re-use sectors, prices did not change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, the largest price increase compared to the same month of the previous year was observed in the energy and reuse sectors (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods manufacturing sectors, we measured a 6.8 percent price increase and in investment goods a 1.4 percent price decrease.
Export sales prices of industry, measured in HUF, increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, and decreased by 3.9 per cent in 12 months.
Our domestic currency weakened by 1.7 per cent against the euro and 7.1 per cent against the dollar in one month, and strengthened by 7.5 per cent against the euro and 15.9 per cent against the dollar in August 2007.
