Lukashenko resistance: 110-0
Not a single member of the opposition has entered the Belarusian parliament following Sunday’s election.
According to Russian observers, this can be explained by the prosperity and stability of the country led by Alexander Lukashenko, but according to the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), the illegalities committed at the time of counting the votes.
The OSCE, which sent 450 observers from 43 countries, did not recognise the elections.
Although the country’s 100-million-strong legislature has been without opposition for more than a decade, before yesterday’s elections, the opposition, united under the name of the United Democratic Forces (ODSZ), seriously hoped that Lukashenko, who renewed his presidential mandate for the fourth time in the controversial elections in 2006, would “allow” some opposition MPs to appear in the parliament.
The ODSZ also withdrew from the previously considered boycott.
The opposition’s expectations were based on the fact that Belarus, which is increasingly economically dependent on Russia – which has taken out loans to reduce the ever-expensive Russian gas imports and has also contributed to the transfer of Beltransgaz, the owner of gas pipelines through the country, into Russian hands – wanted to improve its relations with the EU due to a non-political regime and a high-ranking Belarusian political party, which is considered anti-democratic.
The OSCE’s emphasis on positive moves rather than shortcomings – for example, the banning of a third of opposition candidates – was a relief when evaluating the election campaign.
However, the OSCE's flash report on Monday also criticised the campaign - during which opposition candidates were essentially not allowed to appear in the press - and in particular the fact that the opposition was not able to be present at the counting of votes.
Nevertheless, the opposition said there was a marked improvement in the political system: political prisoners were released and Minsk was willing to face a minor confrontation with Moscow, still refusing to recognise South Ossetia and Abkhazia, which had separated from Georgia, even though Russia, with which Belarus forms a federal state on paper, had considered the two territories independent for a month.
"We have taken two steps forward, one step back, but most importantly, the dialogue between Belarus and the EU has begun," Milinkevich said.
The opposition candidate for the 2006 presidential election said it was “desirable” that this should remain, despite the fact that “the power is afraid of allowing even an opposition to enter the weightless parliament”.
The opposition is not planning any protest actions in view of the results, but rather is trying to convey its message to the voters about the need for economic reforms.
“Of course, we have a lot of problems with this, we have to print opposition newspapers in Russia, the local authorities are putting up barriers to dissemination, but I can see that more and more people support change, including among the elderly,” Milinkevich said, referring to the fact that Lukashenko’s regime, which considers the creation of social security as its main result, is not even suitable for the most officially supported pensioners.
“Because of the country’s indebtedness and the increase in the trade deficit, it’s a matter of time before the social security system that evokes the silence of a cemetery breaks down,” Milinkevich said.
In contrast to the opposition politician, Russian observers described the elections as democratic.
Sergey Lebedev, the head of the CIS mission, told the Russian news agency Ria Novosti that “people believe not in words but in actions”, so the lack of opposition is nothing more than proof of the maturity of the Belarusian electorate.
