MP3 Players Can Cause Hearing Loss
Persistent hearing loss can be caused by listening to portable playback devices for longer periods of time and at high volume, such as MP3s.
In a report published in Brussels, the European Commission, the Scientific Committee on New and Newly Identified Health Risks (SCENIHR) has today published an opinion.
"The study shows that between 5 and 10 percent of people who listen to their portable music players for more than an hour a day for five years with a high volume can suffer permanent hearing loss," the study said.
"It's worrying that young people who use high-volume portable music players and mobile phones on a massive scale are not aware that they can cause irreversible damage to their hearing," said Meglena Kuneva.
"Scientific surveys indicate an undeniable risk that we urgently need to respond to," he added.
The most important task is to inform and disseminate information to consumers on a wide scale.
In the light of this opinion, we also need to review the existing control systems so that they can operate efficiently and keep up with the latest technologies."
Brussels has asked the independent scientific committee to examine the problem in the light of the prevalence of portable music players and the increasing number of young people exposed to the noise they cause.
"Researchers confirm that we have cause for concern, and the European Commission is ready to explore, in cooperation with Member States and stakeholders, possible measures to protect children and young people exposed to noise from portable players and similar devices," said the commissioner.
The current European safety standard sets the maximum sound level emitted by portable music players at 100 dB, but there is an increasing concern about hearing loss data due to the excessive use of such sound sources.
At the same time, there are solutions, such as reducing the level and duration of noise exposure, that can significantly reduce these hearing impairments.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee states that users of portable music players who listen to music at high volumes (more than 89 decibels) for five hours a week have noise exposures that exceed the current maximum level of noise at work.
If a person listens to music for a long time under similar conditions, after five years there is a risk of permanent hearing loss.
This affects around 5-10% of mobile device users, which could amount to between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
