The elite is at risk.
The phenomenon was already felt a few days ago when the House of Representatives refused to vote in favour of the <0x24>700 billion bailout proposed by the White House: a significant portion of Americans were more interested, and still are interested, in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday’s New York Times, which reports that the current crisis has created a breakthrough within the Republican Party, which is showing an increasing division between the traditional, restrained attitude of support for federal institutions and business circles on the East Coast and the growing anti-Washington and anti-financial world stance in the central and southern states.
This has been demonstrated in a critical way in the House vote mentioned in the introduction.
However, this event is only one of the major changes that the economic transformation that is still taking place is predicting or allowing to be seen, not only in the United States, but in the entire Western world, and perhaps even beyond.
It seems that the crisis, both in the US and in Europe, is only accelerating the long-standing latent phenomena that are consolidating in this new atmosphere and are finally coming to light.
The first such phenomenon is the re-actualization, the re-establishment of the dual category of state sovereignty in connection with a kind of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis is affecting those banking and financial institutions that, although they have close ties with the rest of the world, are primarily, and on a fairly large scale, attracting people and families who live in a single country, a single state.
This, in turn, presents a direct political difficulty for those in government: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those who are also electors.
So, in economic terms, the crisis appears to be global, but in political terms it is almost exclusively national.
It seems that political internationalism is essentially stranded off the coast: the European Union is an eloquent proof of this, which is unable to establish a unified political line between different interests and different national strategies.
So everyone expects the intervention, the rescue package, the recovery and the new rules from the individual national governments, but most of all the opening of the funds: because in a situation of need, only the individual states have the economic resources, the financial resources, which may be able to put things in order.
They have the means and the authority to use them: under the circumstances, they have two invaluable resources that probably no other market and no international organisation will ever have to this extent.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed by the crisis on the nation-state is fully in line with the fact that the recent economic growth places increasing importance on a factor that is closely related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had already entered the abstract world of networking, increasingly sophisticated technology, and that the global financial world was destined to dominate the world, we suddenly had to realize that our future was increasingly dependent on less abstract things like water, crops and oil.
Things that can be transported from one side of the planet to the other, but can still be completely connected to a definite place, an area.
So the one who controls the area has far more cards than the one who, unfortunately, was born in a place where there is no crops, no oil, and no water.
I would like to move on to the second novelty, which suggests a kind of fracture line.
Whoever says territory, state, government, must also say politics, in other words, leadership.
From this point of view, the economic crisis seems to produce two conflicting phenomena:
On the one hand, an objective recognition of the need for authentic leadership, by someone who can take control of events.
On the other hand, the current leadership, especially the economic leaders, who have proved to be totally inadequate and have proved that there are still many obscure areas ahead of them, has brought about a complete loss of credibility.
Together, the two are of even deeper significance and, in a sense, more troubling: a sense of loss of credit, impatience, incompetence, and detachment that affects the entire leadership elite in an increasing number of Western countries.
It seems, therefore, that there is a growing belief among the population that the age of the social elite, which is at its peak, is over. It has expired before their actions, experiences, lifestyles, cultures, in the complex sense of the word, were adopted. Thus, the social elite is increasingly alienated from the opinion of the majority.
In a word, the demand for leadership, in a veiled form, fuels a diversified but strong delegitimation movement against the ruling class and the traditional political system. This is manifested in the unexpected "rebellions" of voters, or in recent times in the sudden changes in the mood against the public.
It seems that the traditional elite, with its parties, programs, and even with its habits, press and famous intellectuals, is less and less able to understand and, therefore, less and less able to represent what has been going on for some time in the deeper layers of Western society.
Despite all this, speaking of the “imminent rebellion of the masses” is, frankly, an exaggeration.
