Medications? No fruit juice!
Care should be taken with grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These high-vitamin drinks, which are popular in the summer, if taken with certain life-saving medicines, alter their absorption, increasing or decreasing their effect, depending on the case. This can also have serious health consequences.
David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, pointed out the risks of taking canned or fresh juices with certain medications. The professor announced at the 236th National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia that a glass of grapefruit, orange or apple juice can reduce the absorption of certain life-saving medications, preventing their beneficial effects on the health of the patient.
Grapefruit juice has already been put on the accused’s bench when it was found to be able to increase the effects of some antibiotics, antihistamines, anxiety-reducing, heart rhythm-regulating and neuropharmaceuticals to levels considered toxic.
Two years ago, the Italian Pharmaceutical Institute itself published the news in its official gazette and warned doctors and patients to take the risks associated with this co-administration seriously and to pay attention to what they drink when taking medicines such as Diazepam or Methadone.
NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT – According to researchers, orange and apple juice also contain substances that inhibit the effectiveness of drugs.
The list of active substances whose absorption is hindered by grapefruit and other fruit juices could be long.
Michele Carruba, professor of pharmaceuticals at the Milan State University, said: “Such discoveries are usually immediately reported to the various national and international pharmaceutical institutions, who, if necessary, will ensure that the information contained in the product information is changed.
That’s why you should always read the leaflet of the medicine you are going to take and if something is not understandable, don’t let yourself be influenced, but clearly ask your doctor or pharmacist,” said the specialist at the Ansa Institute.
