Open Office, the third edition of the "Anti-Microsoft" package
Today, OpenOffice.org 3.0, an open-source application suite that enhances personal productivity, is launching as a free alternative to Microsoft Office, targeting a growing range of layers, from home to office users, from freelancers to administrators.
After nearly a year of SUN Microsystem-managed work by volunteer developers, the new Open Office comes to the public with several novelties: in addition to the welcome screen and a redesigned, less Spartan user interface, it also offers several essential novelties, such as compatibility with the Apple Mac OS X operating system and support for the new ISO-standard ODF (Open Document 1.2) format.
Particular attention has been paid to compatibility with Office 2007 so that Open Office can open Microsoft documents with new extensions (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
Interesting also are the specific features of some modules, such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations. This can be useful when sending files by email. Another feature supports importing PDF files into the graphical module, while keeping the page layout.
In the same interface, you can create "hybrid PDF" documents that combine the typical Adobe format with spreadsheet or word processing elements.
Sharing within apps has also undergone a number of improvements: the spreadsheet supports the shared use of workbooks, but prevents overwriting each other’s work. Each employee’s comments are colored differently, which helps to make them easier to recognize during the verification phase.
Some companies are already working on making some of OpenOffice’s features available from the Internet (on the cloud), so the final version is likely to be presented in the coming weeks.
The Italian version can be downloaded from http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html.
The package is available for Linux in addition to standard Windows and Mac OS operating systems.
On request, you can receive the installation CD at home or at work.
In terms of the home app’s spread, it’s probably the most appealing, but the Open Office suite is now trying to kick the ball in the business sector as it can count on a number of administrative and school projects.
There is no shortage of training, consulting and service services that are ideal for small and medium-sized enterprises, which can open up new business prospects.
Open Office consists of five core modules: Writer, a word-based word processor; Calc, a spreadsheet designed to replace Excel; Impress, Powerpoint-like presentations; Dbase is the most well-known, similar to Access Database Manager; and finally Draw is the graphical module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads. But if you take into account that we are already at 3,600,000 with the release of the new version, this number is likely to be higher than expected.
