Goodbye, old Cinema Paradiso, the days of the old cinemas are over in the cities
Traditional cinemas are closing in favor of Multiplexes.
“A city without cinemas, a blind city, is like a face without eyes.”
The pictures taken by director Giuseppe Tornatore are an impressive representation of what is happening in Italian cities, but also in rural areas.
The displacement of cinemas - the appearance of large, multi-room cinemas in the suburbs, and consequently the atrophy of one-room cinemas in city centers - seems inevitable and irreversible, but at the same time bears all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
When places full of history and memories disappear, "it's like a friend who's gone, a acquaintance with whom we shared our journey and many experiences," says the director of Cinema Paradiso. The film, which was an Oscar 20 years ago, as well as the Grand Prix of the Cannes Festival for Tornatore, is lost after all a lyrical story of a small-town cinema, perhaps, a story of longing
The figures published by Anec, the largest association of operators, are clear: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed. The biggest losses were recorded by cinemas in large cities: 10 cinemas closed in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna, which has lost 82 one-room cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And the fact that multiplexes are the cause of their disappearance is no better evidence than the fact that in these three regions of Italy, the number of newly opened multi-room cinemas is the highest: in the last five years, the number of rooms in Lombardy has increased by 195, in Tuscany by 81 and in Emilia-Romagna by the same amount.
"The number of units in Italy has increased irrationally," says Anec President Paolo Protti. "It is okay to build new facilities, but we should also ensure the survival of the existing ones, because when a city cinema closes, not all of the passageways are willing to go through multiplexes.
Not to mention the unfilled financial funds to support operators: the overdue debt of the State is estimated at around EUR 10 million.
It is both ethically and morally disgraceful that the government does not comply with the legislation in force.
It would require between <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>16 and <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>18 million a year to maintain the market.”
It is the first Italian city, concerned about closures, that has decided to remedy the problem through an agreement between the municipality and Anec in order to protect and boost one-room cinemas in the outer and inner city.
The provisions would include tax incentives for operators, as well as benefits for the public to facilitate accessibility: viewers can enter restricted areas and park at reduced rates in certain parking lots.
"I like this initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities, even with other measures, will follow the example of Bologna.
But it is also certain that traditional cinemas need to improve sound and image quality in order to be able to fight the dominance of multiplexes, because today’s audience is much more demanding.
The preservation of traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of Supercinema in Bagheria, where I spent my childhood and youth, gave me the spark that made me finally do Cinema Paradiso, even though I’ve been thinking about it for 10 years.
