The energy comes from the waves, and now the big ones come
An inexhaustible source of energy that accounts for 70 percent of the planet’s surface and is still being discovered by major international energy companies.
Waves, ocean currents, tides, all renewable energy sources that giants like Chevron have been looking for and are now trying to get their hands on it.
For a hundred years, they've been researching how to extract energy from the movements of the sea, and in the 1970s, during the first oil crisis, research was intensifying.
Around 1980, when oil prices fell, the idea of exploiting offshore energy was put aside, but today the demand for environmental protection and the re-emergence of oil prices give the sector a new impetus.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by installations that utilize the waves of the sea.
This is twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there would be currents and tides.
Giants are on the rise.
Enersis was the first company to commit to offshore energy and in 2005 signed an agreement for a power plant in northern Portugal.
It seemed like a revolutionary step when the signature was announced.
Two years have passed since then, and more and more companies are opting for marine energy, including those who have been committed to conventional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies and is considering working with us," a spokesperson for an affiliate of the U.S. oil giant, the Wall Street Journal, said in a statement.
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a permit issued by the U.S. Energy Commission to launch a project in Alaska for the exploitation of marine energy.
This is of no small importance, especially considering that the US is currently producing oil in Alaska, and President Bush has just launched a plan for further drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. in New York and Ocean Power in New Jersey are also on the path to energy from the sea. The amount invested so far, as far as the details are known, is proving to be of growing interest.
Technology is waiting to be developed.
According to experts, it is still a rudimentary technology, only because the energy from the sea does not dispel doubts about the environmental impact.
The existing facilities, such as those in Portugal or Scotland, are all small in size and therefore do not pose too much of a problem for the ecosystem.
However, in order to produce energy on a larger scale, we need facilities that also have a greater impact on the environment.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses an interconnected buoy system.
The shocks generated by the waves and moving the buoys up and down are transformed into hydraulic pressure by the pistons and cylinders placed in them.
The pressure rotates a turbine, which feeds a generator.
Electricity flows to land via cables under the sea.
At the moment, there are four similar facilities in the planning phase, which are only waiting for federal approval, and part of the energy generated would be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started generating power for a shopping mall and a parking lot with six submarine turbines located in the East River Strait of New York.
At tides, the movement of water rotates the turbine blades, and this rotational movement feeds the generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of partners who are just waiting for the necessary permits to use energy.
Waves after tides.
At present, the opportunities that can be exploited through the tides deserve special attention.
Although it is a periodic phenomenon, tides are more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and can therefore be considered a more reliable source of energy.
